  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why Houzz doesn't build on resolution?",
  "response": "Houzz, a popular platform for home design and renovation, may not prioritize building on resolution for several reasons:\n\n1. **Complexity of Design Projects**: Home design and renovation projects are inherently complex, involving multiple stakeholders (homeowners, architects, contractors, etc.) and numerous variables (budgets, timelines, materials, etc.). This complexity can make it challenging to create a unified resolution system that addresses all aspects of these projects effectively.\n\n2. **Focus on Visual Inspiration**: Houzz primarily emphasizes visual inspiration and discovery. The platform is designed to help users find design ideas, products, and professionals. Building on resolution (if by \"resolution\" you mean conflict resolution or project management) might divert focus from its core mission of providing inspiration and connecting users with professionals.\n\n3. **Platform Ecosystem**: Houzz has developed an ecosystem that includes design ideas, product purchases, and professional services. While it offers tools like project management and communication features, these are supplementary to its main offerings. Incorporating a robust resolution system might require significant changes to its existing structure and could complicate the user experience.\n\n4. **Industry Practices**: The construction and design industries often handle disputes and resolutions through traditional means, such as contracts, legal agreements, and direct communication between parties. Houzz might prefer to leave these aspects to the professionals and their clients, rather than getting directly involved in dispute resolution.\n\n5. **User Expectations**: Users of Houzz primarily seek inspiration, products, and professionals. They may not expect or require the platform to mediate disputes or manage project resolutions. Houzz\u2019s value proposition lies in its ability to connect users with the right resources and ideas, rather than in resolving conflicts.\n\n6. **Regulatory and Legal Considerations**: Handling disputes and resolutions can involve navigating complex legal and regulatory landscapes. By not building a formal resolution system, Houzz may avoid potential legal liabilities and regulatory challenges.\n\n7. **Resource Allocation**: Developing and maintaining a comprehensive resolution system would require significant resources, including technology, personnel, and expertise. Houzz might allocate its resources towards enhancing its core offerings, such as improving the search and discovery experience, expanding its product catalog, and refining its professional matching services.\n\nIn summary, Houzz likely avoids building on resolution because it aligns with its core mission of providing design inspiration and connecting users with professionals, while the complexities and legal implications of handling disputes do not align with its primary business model.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
